==English==

===Etymology===
See {{etyl|fr}} ''[[abusif]]'', from {{etyl|la}} ''[[abusivus]]''

===Pronunciation===
* {{IPA|/əˈbuːsɪv/}}

===Adjective===
{{en-adj}}

# [[wrongly|Wrongly]] used; [[perverted]]; [[misapplied]].
#: I am ... necessitated to use the word Parliament improperly, according to the '''abusive''' acceptation thereof. - [[Fuller]]
# {{archaic}} Given to [[misusing]]; also, full of abuses.
#:* The '''abusive''' prerogatives of his see. - [[w:Henry Hallam|Hallam]]
# [[practicing|Practicing]] abuse; [[prone]] to ill treat by coarse, [[insulting]] words or by other ill usage; as, an '''abusive''' author; an '''abusive''' fellow.
# Containing abuse, or serving as the instrument of abuse; [[vituperative]]; [[reproachful]]; [[scurrilous]].
#:* An '''abusive''' lampoon. - [[w:Samuel Johnson|Samuel Johnson]] ''A dictionary of the English language''
# {{obsolete}} Tending to deceive; [[fraudulent]]; [[cheating]].
#:* An '''abusive''' treaty. - [[w:Francis Bacon|Francis Bacon]]

